docs\development.md:56:Inline migrations in `models/db.js` must **quote mixed-case identifiers**. Sequelize quotes all identifiers, so a model column like `rfqItem_price_sales_snapshots` is queried case-sensitively. An unquoted `ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS rfqItem_price_sales_snapshots` is folded to lowercase by Postgres, creating a column Sequelize can never find → `RFQItem.findAll` throws → `main.controller` returns SYS-002 and the RFQ grid shows "no rows to show". Always quote: `ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS "rfqItem_price_sales_snapshots" TEXT`. Regression-guarded in `tests/unit/db.migration.test.js` (see AGENTS.md §14, SYS-002).
docs\deployment.md:27:There is no separate migration job. On **every container start**, `models/db.js` (loaded via `index.js`) runs a sequence of idempotent inline migrations against the database — `ALTER TABLE "RFQItem"/"Factory"/"users"/"customers"/"vendor"/"RFQVendor" ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS ...`, `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS app_settings`, `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ai_cache_events`, and a `Factory.factory_country` backfill `UPDATE`. A schema change ships by adding an `ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS` or `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS` statement to `models/db.js`; the new column/table is only realized in an environment once the new revision boots.
docs\deployment.md:40:**Mixed-case column identifiers MUST be double-quoted** in these statements. Sequelize quotes all identifiers; Postgres folds unquoted ones to lowercase. An unquoted `ADD COLUMN` created an orphan `rfqitem_price_sales_snapshots` that broke the RFQ grid (SYS-002, fixed in `a556d3f`). See AGENTS.md §14.
